<br>
His warm glow emitted into the air, as he floated a few feet above the battle, his arms crossed about his chest. His wounds had healed. One of the perks of being a divine figure. He was not dressed as he was before, he wore a blood red tunic. His knee-length cape was of gold as were his golden sandles, and golden laurel crown. He stood there, son of Leto and Zeus, in his ever benevolent splendor.<br>
<br>
A wind gushed across the lush plain of the blood stained battlefield. The night had fallen upon the battle, and Apollo acted as a flashlight to the battle before him, slightly illuminating the night. His cape blew in the twilight breeze.<br>
<br>
&quot;Poseidon's getting his just desserts.&quot; thought Apollo, a small ominous grin on his face. He slightly enjoyed watching the torturing of his Uncle. Surely he was going to lose this battle in the long run. Three immortals on one, even if he was third in power to Zeus after himself. Ares, alone was a force to be reckoned with on the battlefield. He was in his element, and even though Apollo and Ares rarely saw eye to eye, Apollo saw beauty in the almost poetic movements of Ares on the battlefield.<br>
<br>
&quot;Poseidon it seems you have bitten off just a bit more than you can chew dearest Uncle.&quot; Apollo finally spoke, making his presence known to the four immortals. That demeaning grin was cast on his face, was he to await the inevitable debacle of Poseidon, or participate in his lashing, only adding insult to injury?<br>
<br>
&quot;Do tell me O, trident-bearing Lord of the Deep. Do you think you can take on this immense challenge on your own account? Or have you seen the foolishness in your action, and implore assistance from any enigma that happens to wander it's way into ear shot of your plea? Poseidon, has your years of being a second to Father Zeus, the Aegis-bearing Lord of the Heavens, gone to your head? Do you not realize that others have succeeded your reign? Before you lies a new generation Uncle. I am the voice of 2nd generation Olympia, and I will be heard. Your tyrannical reign over all under you has come to pass, it is now I, and I alone who hold the key to the future. Though your years and experience give you and advantage, do not underestimate the gift of sheer and raw power. I am not threatening, but promising you Poseidon, that if you do not fight with your rage aside, it will lead to your downfall. Take this, coming from a god who knows all of what has happened and all that will happen.&quot; Apollo's brow perked, his grin casted to Poseidon.<br>
<br>
Another gush of wind blew as Apollo stood there in all his glory, the wind whipping his garments around. Would perhaps Poseidon listen to Apollo's divine advice, or would he again dive foolishly into a situation he would not be able to wriggle out of? <p>      *~*The Golden God*~*
